metadata.name: Dencity #921
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Dialect: Bold #35
metadata.description:
Dialect: Bold is the wild younger sibling of Dialect. As both Dialect collections are created using a string of text as the main input, "Bold" is also a play on the term used to denote the weight of a font. Many aesthetic decisions were made along the way to completing Dialect. Dialect: Bold is what would have happened had a different path been taken. Complimentary but different. Bold!

metadata.name: Pigments #107
metadata.description:
‚ÄúPigments‚Äù is a generative art project that explores the beauty of optical color blending and the power of noise. 

At the heart of this work is a random composition of rectangles that are made up of dots. These pigments are arranged in multiple layers, each layer using a different color from one of the carefully curated color palettes. Each palette consists of three to five colors. 

As the pigments are shifted by random noise, new hues and patterns emerge, creating a lovely display of color and movement.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[5] to change the resolution.
- Press [s] to save a png file at the current resolution.

This is my first generative art project. Created with p5js.

________

Looks best on high-resolution screens and viewed in live mode. When displayed on a low-resolution screen, an unintended moir√© pattern may appear.

objkt.name: Romeo and Juliet on Punched Cards (Free) #18

metadata.name: Romeo and Juliet on Punched Cards (Free) #18
metadata.description:
This artwork takes a modern approach to printing Shakespeare's classic play, Romeo and Juliet. The text is printed on old punched cards from an IBM machine from the 1970s, giving it a vintage look and feel. The lines of text are selected randomly from the play, creating a unique and dynamic representation of the story.

But there's a twist - the text on the punched cards is actually readable by the old machines, but it doesn't make sense to them. This highlights the stark contrast between the old and new technologies and how much has changed since the 1970s. Despite the advancements in technology, however, the beauty and significance of Romeo and Juliet remain timeless.

This artwork is a celebration of the past, present, and future, and the ways in which technology has evolved and continues to shape our lives.

Additionally, to ensure a fair distribution of the text from Romeo and Juliet, only 1024 tokens were selected at random. This allows for a diverse range of quotes and scenes to be included in the artwork, while still capturing the essence of the play as a whole. Whether you're a Shakespeare enthusiast or a tech-savvy individual, this artwork offers something for everyone to appreciate.

metadata.name: Squiggsli #40
metadata.description:
Squiggsli is a petulant teenager, living in the decadent times during the last days of #fxhash 1.0.
He spends hours staring blankly at his glitchy old computer monitor, his reflection mirroring the ennui of his existence overlaid on the ever-changing chaotic turmoil of his society.

Press "p" to suspend the chaos for a while, and "s" to capture a slice of his life, encoded in a 640x640 pixel png file.

metadata.name: Concrete #156
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksj√∏ (1910‚Äì1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksj√∏ designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksj√∏‚Äôs aim was to ‚Äúsoften‚Äù modernist architecture. He invented ¬´Natural Concrete¬ª, a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions‚Äîusing code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksj√∏: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‚ÄòS‚Äô to save an image at current resolution or ‚ÄòP‚Äô to save a high-resolution file at 6000√ó6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau ¬∑ Made with p5.js & glsl ¬∑ Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #209
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)
